  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Formerly called \"central pontine myelinolysis\"\nA neurologic condition caused by rapid correction of hyponatremia, with starting serum sodium normally 120 meq/L or less\nCaused by rapid correction of hyponatremia (>12 mEq/L/24 h), as water moves from cells to extracellular fluid, yielding intracellular dehydration.\nSymptoms are often irreversible or only partially reversible",
      "subsections": {
        "Risk_Factors": {
          "text": "Chronic\nheart failure\nAlcoholism\nCirrhosis\nHypokalemia\nMalnutrition\nTreatment with vasopressin antagonists (e.g. tolvaptan)",
          "tables": []
        },
        "Risk_Factors_for_Over-correction": {
          "text": "Lower initial sodium\nSchizophrenia\nLower baseline urine sodium",
          "tables": []
        }
      },
